\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Distribution of records across all 41 disease classes in the dataset~\cite  {itachi2020}. Each bar represents one disease; the dataset is approximately balanced with roughly 120 records per class (range: 114--132). This near-uniform distribution means accuracy is a meaningful evaluation metric --- no classifier can inflate its score simply by predicting the most frequent class. The balanced distribution also eliminates the need for class-weighting or oversampling techniques such as SMOTE~\cite  {chawla2002smote} in our pipeline. As discussed in Section~\ref {sec:results}, the stratified 80/20 split preserves these proportions in both the training and test subsets. Generated using Seaborn (see Cell~7 in the Appendix).}}{12}{figure.caption.4}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:classdist}{{2}{12}{Distribution of records across all 41 disease classes in the dataset~\cite {itachi2020}. Each bar represents one disease; the dataset is approximately balanced with roughly 120 records per class (range: 114--132). This near-uniform distribution means accuracy is a meaningful evaluation metric --- no classifier can inflate its score simply by predicting the most frequent class. The balanced distribution also eliminates the need for class-weighting or oversampling techniques such as SMOTE~\cite {chawla2002smote} in our pipeline. As discussed in Section~\ref {sec:results}, the stratified 80/20 split preserves these proportions in both the training and test subsets. Generated using Seaborn (see Cell~7 in the Appendix)}{figure.caption.4}{}}
